    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "To the editor:",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "The outbreak of SARS-CoV-2 and COVID-19 pandemic represent an international public health emergency [1]. Patients with cancer are at higher risk of developing severe COVID-19 manifestations and hence the whole clinical decision making process for oncological care is being revised, in order to balance the risk-benefit ratio for each treatment offered to patients [2, 3, 4, 5, 6]. This scenario forces healthcare providers, including radiotherapy professionals, to undergo substantial reorganization in terms of staffing, resources, working processes, treatment allocation and delivery and safety measures [7,8]. This situation is supposed to have practical and psychological consequences on both cancer patients and healthcare workers. This is even magnified on a personal level, since the response required by the COVID-19 pandemic, calls for draconian measures (quarantine for entire communities, social isolation), which are a potential source of further distress [9,10]. Individuals facing traumatic events usually experience distressing emotions such as anxiety, sadness, guilt, and anger. For healthcare providers, an important stressor is related to the fear of being exposed to SARS-CoV-2 at hospital and the consequent anxiety of bringing the infection home [9]. For cancer patients, the fear of being infected adds up to the cancer condition, which represents \u2018per se\u2019 a traumatic event. Exposure to trauma is usually associated to psychological distress and Trauma- and Stressor-Related Disorders such as post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD). High levels of PTSD were observed amongst medical staff during the H7N9 avian flu outbreak [11]. Nevertheless, the presence of negative consequences in the aftermath of the trauma does not exclude the possibility to develop also positive outcomes thereafter [12, 13]. Indeed, trauma can be a fertile ground for an unexpected outcome observed in survivors: posttraumatic growth (PTG). PTG refers to \u201cpositive psychological change experienced as a result of the struggle with highly challenging life circumstances\u201d [14]. The Posttraumatic Growth Inventory (PTGI) is the most reliable measure to evaluate the positive change following a traumatic event. It measures five domains:a) appreciation of life;b) intimate relationships with others;c) sense of personal strength;d) recognition of new possibilities;e) spiritual change [15].",
