        },
        {
            "text": "Growth, however, does not occur as a direct result of trauma. Different factors could foster the development of PTG. They are related to sociodemographic features like age (higher growth for younger individuals), personality characteristics (extraversion, open-mindedness to experience) and coping strategies to manage distressing emotions. Crucial is also the activation of a cognitive processing allowing individuals to disengage with previous core beliefs and to build new schemas and meanings. Eventually, the presence of a social support can help in elaborating narratives about the traumatic event experienced [14].",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 617,
                    "end": 619,
                    "mention": "14",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "In conclusion, traumatic and stressful events, like the COVID-19 pandemic, have definitely negative acute effects, but can lead to mid- to long-term positive outcomes. Hence, both healthcare providers and cancer patients should be supported whenever experiencing psychological distress or difficulties in changing personal cognitive beliefs or struggling for the lack of social help. This would be important to foster the process of positive growth.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        }
